Roeder himself, omitting St. Luke’s sab- bath and Pentecost, and adding the regular sabbath on the 12th Tisri and the Feast of Tabernacles on the leth, makes that the great day in question. The opinion of Scaliger was, that the Jews observed the 30th day of each mouth as a sabbath. Gesner and Doering, and some others, follow Scaliger. Others suppose the day of the Passover to be the sabbath in ques- tion, and by calculatione try ιο prove that it might have been. 1 do not find that it is made out on any authority that the Jews had any sabbath that they called the thir- tieth, and I very much doubt the fact. The utter contempt with which the Romans, especially of Horace’s class, looked upon the J ewish superstitious (as they counted them), is the essence of the joke in the text. That the Jews had a sabbath of course every body knew. That they had a sabba- tical year and a year of J ubilee no doubt was known to some, and that this came round every finey year-ag also that they obses-ved days and months and years with scrupulous exactness.
